<p class = 'definition' data-word = "Newton's Third Law">
  Whenever A exerts a force on B,
  then B exerts a force on A
  with equal magnitude and opposite direction.
  These two forces are called an <em>action-reaction pair</em>.
</p>

<h4>
  Rigorously Describing Reaction Forces
</h4>

<p>
  Newton's Third Law states that two forces always come in <strong>pairs</strong>,
  which are called <em>action-reaction pairs</em>.
</p>

<ul class="definition" data-word = 'reaction force'>
    <li>
        The <em>agent</em> of the reaction force is the object of the original force.
    </li>
    <li>
        The <em>object</em> of the reaction force is the agent of the original force.
    </li>
    <li>
        The <em>magnitude</em> of the reaction force is the same as the magnitude of the original force.
    </li>
    <li>
        The <em>direction</em> of the reaction force is opposite the direction of the original force.
    </li>
</ul>

<h5>
    Examples:
</h5>

<ul>
    <li>
        Muhammad Ali's fist punches Joe Frazier's face to the left with 500 N of force.
        <ul>
            <li>
                The agent of the reaction force is Joe Frazier's face.
            </li>
            <li>
                The object of the reaction force is Muhammad Ali's fist.
            </li>
            <li>
                The magnitude of the reaction force is 500 N.
            </li>
            <li>
                The direction of the reaction force is to the right.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
