<h4>
  An Advanced Point
</h4>

<p>
  Newton's Third Law states that forces always come in pairs.
  Even though we call them "action-reaction pairs",
  it is important to note that there aren't really two different forces,
  one "action" and another "reaction."
  What's really happening is that two forces occur simultaneously all of the time:
  whenever there is one force, there is always another.
  One force didn't come first and the other second;
  whenever there is one force, the other is there, always.
</p>

<p>
  We call then an "action-reaction pair" because those are the words that Isaac Newton used,
  and the term is intuitive, but that isn't really correct!
  They are simply a pair of forces that exist together.
</p>


